Rakuen's founding ideals and present reality coexist under permanent tension.
Paradise Thesis claims: abundance over debt, rotating stewardship, mediation over tribunal, low-wall principle, forest integration.
What these became: the Garden Ledger (public-abundance tracker converted to scarcity management within forty years), the Bloom Council's tenure system (rotates titles; professional advisors who never rotate hold institutional memory), Ember Wardens' emergency adjudication, ration towers and causeway walls (classified as "emergency welfare infrastructure"), and genuine root-weave lower terraces alongside upper city stone the Woodland treats as obstruction.
The Promise Stones — carved granite markers inscribed with compact pledges — exist in every neighborhood; most are cracked or ash-stained; defacing one remains a serious social offense.
The Bloom Council's curated Paradise Thesis omits the sections most critical of Midgaard; the Garden Ledger Clerks have never fully forgiven this.
