The three Rakuen annexation refusals can be measured against stated justifications and observable outcomes.
Southmark Petition refused on ledger-compliance grounds. Rakuen reformatted its Garden Ledger. The Ash Plea refusal had nothing to do with ledger format — demonstrating the stated reason was not the operative reason.
Ash Plea refused on route-instability grounds. The joint route-stability commission met four times and produced zero binding agreements. The route instability was cited as a barrier while no action removed it.
Iron Compact Appeal refused on charter-sovereignty grounds with a note suggesting Rakuen amend its Compact — a path Midgaard neither facilitated nor committed to recognizing.
Pattern: each refusal cited a different administrative reason; after the first barrier was addressed, a different barrier was substituted, then another.
Empirical record: three barriers cited, one addressed, two substituted, no annexation.
