Rakuen's disaster stacking during the Ash-and-Iron Decades included Cinderteeth volcanic consequences: ash-laden rain clogged cisterns, soured roof-catchments, and poisoned kitchen gardens.
The canopy ash-load increased branchfall mortality and turned hearth smoke into chronic respiratory hazard in low terraces.
Midgaard's emergency aid convoys were classified as "southern variance relief" — no legal accountability — while the Bloom Council filed three formal protests that received no substantive response.
For Ashborn communities, the ash-load mortality is not historical abstraction but family memory: the cisterns that failed, the roofs that held ash weight until collapse.
The Bloom Council's acceptance of the "variance relief" classification rather than contesting it is one of the grievances the Honest Ledger movement and Route Realist bloc cite.
